Abdul Qadeer Khan, known as the father of the Pakistani atomic bomb, supplied weapons-grade uranium to Iran in 2001.
An Iranian opposition group claims Iran aims to acquire a nuclear bomb soon.
South Africa and Libya were also involved in illicit nuclear technology transfers.
Pakistan denies collaborating with the US to target Iranian weapons sites.
Khan, under house arrest, confessed to nuclear leaks to Iran, Libya, and North Korea.
The US refrains from direct access to Khan to avoid straining relations with Pakistan.
The International Atomic Energy Agency continues to investigate Iran's nuclear activities.
Pakistan asserts its cooperation with nuclear proliferation control efforts.
